    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 3200, 4100, 4200, 4300, 4400, 7300, 7400, 7500, 7600, 8500, 8600
        Models Built After 05/19/2003 - ELECTRONIC GAUGE CLUSTER AND AUXILIARY GAUGE SWITCH PACK - TROUBLESHOOTING -
        AUDIBLE ALARM
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="x0825407" svcproctype="troubleshoot" graphiccount="1">
        <title>AUDIBLE ALARM</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Circuit Function</title>
            <figure id="f08254a51" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg08/G0825440.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Audible Alarm Function Diagram</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. ELECTRICAL SYSTEM CONTROLLER</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. DRIVE TRAIN 1939 DATA LINK</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. ELECTRONIC GAUGE CLUSTER (EGC)</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>The
                <hotlnk xrefid="f08254a51">audible alarm</hotlnk>
                is controlled by the EGC.
            </para>
            <para>The EGC will activate the alarm based on the data communicated on the Drivetrain 1939 data link from
                the ESC and the engine controller.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Diagnostics</title>
            <para>An inoperative alarm can be caused by a malfunctioning alarm or a malfunction in EGC circuitry.</para>
